>>114315858
It's ok :)

Nah, this is a limiter you put on your master bus (which ALL your tracks go through), to generally catch peaks. People tend to use them to control dynamics and get tracks as loud as possible to complete in the loudness wars. I assumed you were using one because your track is fairly un-dynamic, but that might just mean you're going over 0 and clipping off all the peaks.

posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
>>114315858
>>114315733
It is simply a ceiling for your whole track. You are pushing the loudness towards a limit, and everything above that limit gets cut off. If you push too hard it sounds distorted, if you push it to the sweet spot you achieve loudness and a coherent mix.

posts.com:
>Elvis Costello Live 1977 Chicago
>First generation pop-punk, British Power Pop
This has been released under the titles Armed and Dangerous, as well as Exit, but this is the actual soundboard recording used for the WXRT "Unconcert" broadcast in 1978. (Called Unconcert because it was sponsored by 7-Up, The "Un-Cola") Believe it or not, Tom Petty and The Heartbreakers were the opening act at this show. This was just before Elvis Costello and The Attractions made their debut on Saturday Night Live, subbing for The Sex Pistols who cancelled. (THANKS, MALCOLM!) My Aim is True had just been released, but This Year's Model was just a few months away. (Songs from TYM were played at this show)
When you listen to this concert, you'll understand immediately why Elvis Costello and The Attractions were considered a "Punk" band, and why the first generation of punk rockers adopted them as their own until 1980.

Again, no video. My apologies.

>>114322236
Honestly you could throw a dart at any of the theory books and not really go wrong, ONLY as long as you read multiple texts. I've seen music professors RAIL against the Kostka, like it was the worst thing ever concocted by man. How much of the complaining is bullshit, who knows. You may as well read it, but again I would supplement with other books too.
Harmony and Voice Leading probably isn't the most appropriate book on second thought. It will give you a good foundation, but it is not very forgiving. However, it is basically the voice leading bible. It would be a great text to read as you progress in your knowledge. I've heard good things about Burstein/Straus's Concise Introduction to Tonal Harmony, so you may give that a shot.

>>114328375
>I swear Fripp has DMCAsense.
It's less Robert and more whoever he pays to perform the checks. What is unique is Robert has any say in that at all, since he more-or-less personally controls the rights these days.

Companies used to be much more aggressive about taking down torrents and DDL merely from being linked around, and once it became widespread in the late 90s dedicated record companies pushed for the DCMA, and third parties emerged that used both automated and manual lurklng methods to efficiently play that game of whack-a-mole. This ultimately climaxed with that Youtube v. Viacom case years back where while Youtube/Google ultimately did survive as a free uploading site, they were compelled to implement a more stringent self-check for copyright than even the DCMA limited to avoid a new incident, ContentID.

Since the most popular media sites tend to use something like ContentID or other copyright discovery tools, make their own individual agreements with the right holders, and copyright holders are increasingly comfortable with the idea of creative borrowing that defines online culture, I've noticed that DDL and P2P sharing has had relatively little persecution in the late 2010s and now, though the scene has also similarly suffered a decline with proprietary alternatives being viable.

The first thing you need to understand about this album is that all 3 musicians are playing their instruments with the same concept.

>Mixing board, but with no input.
>Sampler, but with no samples in it.
>Turntable, but with no records playing.
Their technology is stripped of all non-essential audio sources, making their sound palettes as fundamental as possible, either resembling pure electricity or being constituted of pure sine waves.

The second thing you need to understand is that the music is to be listened to "vertically" as opposed to "horizontally." This means that one sound is not to be considered as following another in a linear progression through time, like how a melody is composed of one note following another. The changes in sound are meant to "stack" on each other to create complex timbres. The album's theme (times of day) is an ironic nod to the fact that it is not in time.

The sounds are as simple as possible to give the musicians precision of timbre. This gives them more control over the new timbres they're able to create from the most simple sounds. If they used complex sounds like chords or samples, it would just be a mess and the effect would be completely ruined. They start with silence and surgically alter it.

The third thing you need to understand is that this record is held in high regard by veterans of the EAI scene because it represented a critical juncture in the development of Japanese experimental music. Rather than focusing on "interplay" and "dynamics" between musicians, it shifted its focus solely to the experience imparted upon the listener. Although what they're doing is building sounds, they're more concerned with building the listening experience of those sounds. GMGN literally modifies the way silence "sounds" if you listen to it correctly. It changes your un/conscious experience.

The negative attention it has attracted on RYM has created a false impression of disreputability and frivolity for new listeners.

>Good Morning Good Night is a very conscious step in a new direction, an attempt to create a "vertical" music (as opposed to most music, which moves in a linear, horizontal plane).
To give a short reasoning, while the dynamic in most collaborations focuses on interplay between musicians (and past sounds), GMGN attempts to build vertically- i.e. not based on what you have done before / what the other musician is doing. They are attempting to submit sounds fully "in the moment." Might sounds like a pointless distinction but it's a specific headspace that is extremely difficult (if not impossible) to achieve. Any semblance of horizontal development is meant to be the result of the listener's attention / bias, not the performers.

Yeah some people can't hack it which I think is totally normal.

>can someone explain why (((they))) changed A432hz to A440Hz?
It didn't really happen. A432hz "being the norm" is complete revisionism. The only place that actually used it as their norm was the Paris conservatory and that's pretty much it. There was no strict prior norm before A440hz. However, the A440hz being mainly pushed by american organizations and the ISO made a lot of people weary that there could be more at play. Especially during the new-age era that was begging to find "universal natural resonance" in things and prove that the evil US gubmint was trying to withhold the people's spiritual awakening, etc.
What happened really was international orchestras needing standards, A440hz being an easy norm to remember and its only competition being a niche norm that was only regionally used, or old traditions that would keep being used (ie : A465hz for baroque music)
There's been attempts at justifying something else based on physical phenomenons, as has been done when codifying the length of a second on the vibrations of a cesium atom.
